WEBVTT

00:00:00.434 --> 00:00:07.722
[sounds of thunder and typing]

00:00:08.254 --> 00:00:10.674 line:1
(Geoff Sirc) So, and this is like Longinus
you know

00:00:10.757 --> 00:00:13.307 line:1
we don’t want to persuade people
when we write.

00:00:13.412 --> 00:00:15.522 line:1
What we want to do is blow their head off,

00:00:15.603 --> 00:00:16.948 line:1
and you know I get that.

00:00:17.007 --> 00:00:18.147 line:1
We want to amaze them,

00:00:18.226 --> 00:00:19.886 line:1
and so that leads Longinus

00:00:20.006 --> 00:00:21.926 line:1
to talking about the rhetorical figures.

00:00:21.980 --> 00:00:23.700 line:1
And those little snippets in those

00:00:23.874 --> 00:00:25.684
In the cool [Sirc fades out]

00:00:25.798 --> 00:00:28.758
(Male narrator) Geoff Sirc loves
Longinus.

00:00:28.971 --> 00:00:32.131
And those short snippets that lead to
the sublime.

00:00:32.479 --> 00:00:34.659 line:1
One of my favorites snippets is

00:00:34.659 --> 00:00:37.989 line:1
“The Red Wheelbarrow,” by
William Carlos Williams.

00:00:38.358 --> 00:00:41.228 line:1
The poem has been called
a Rorschach’s blot

00:00:41.228 --> 00:00:45.228 line:1
for the way its opening stanza evokes
the whole metaphysical project.

00:00:45.604 --> 00:00:49.571 line:1
What is it that depends? Anything.

00:00:51.587 --> 00:00:53.167 line:1
And everything.

00:00:54.022 --> 00:00:57.432 line:1
The structure of the poem
whets our anticipation

00:00:57.687 --> 00:01:01.837 line:1
with the enjambed, so much depends, pause

00:01:02.509 --> 00:01:04.769 line:1
upon white space

00:01:05.830 --> 00:01:08.810
Then the piece pulls back with particulars

00:01:08.810 --> 00:01:10.847
that border on the banal.

00:01:11.450 --> 00:01:13.650
It’s driven the critics nuts.

00:01:14.280 --> 00:01:16.925 line:1
Some say, the poem is about labor.

00:01:17.365 --> 00:01:19.775 line:1
Some say, the modern condition.

00:01:20.090 --> 00:01:23.000 line:1
But my favorite: a certain cast of light.

00:01:23.425 --> 00:01:26.025
(Geoff Sirc) You know the way
that I would do, you know

00:01:26.025 --> 00:01:27.128
a happening classroom,

00:01:27.132 --> 00:01:29.852
because you know, I mean students come in
and immediately

00:01:29.895 --> 00:01:32.241
it’s a different atmosphere. 
That's what you want

00:01:32.262 --> 00:01:34.702
You want to just change the
atmosphere in the room

00:01:34.812 --> 00:01:38.352
so that they’re not breathing the same old
college-expectation atmosphere.

00:01:38.557 --> 00:01:43.638
It’s a different climate and, you know,
ah, so, so there.

00:01:44.496 --> 00:01:47.326
(Narrator) Viewing the poem as about
a cast of light

00:01:47.326 --> 00:01:50.556
and thinking about atmosphere leads us to

00:01:50.556 --> 00:01:54.076
the theoretical portion of this
alternative response.

00:01:55.668 --> 00:01:59.668
Happenings can’t be uncoupled
from their space and time.

00:02:00.981 --> 00:02:06.541
They are atmospheric events,
like the weather, like compositions.

00:02:06.882 --> 00:02:10.182
(Sirc) Let’s spend like a day on the
sonnet and let’s just, you know

00:02:10.182 --> 00:02:12.562
let's just marvel at this, you know.
Or whatever

00:02:12.652 --> 00:02:15.672
Because, you know, it’s just, it's just

00:02:15.826 --> 00:02:19.566
language, I think is what’s, is what’s
for me happening.

00:02:20.551 --> 00:02:24.551
(Narrator) So now we’ve linked
composing with the weather.

00:02:24.712 --> 00:02:27.102
We just need to add chickens.

00:02:28.241 --> 00:02:31.231
Let’s start with a scene
outside of a window.

00:02:31.730 --> 00:02:35.440
This is looking out from my house
on the front yard.

00:02:35.696 --> 00:02:37.906
And now let’s add some trickery.

00:02:38.239 --> 00:02:42.239
This is my laptop set up to record
a performance of some music.

00:02:42.613 --> 00:02:46.983
And a projector set up to cast images
of moving hands

00:02:47.184 --> 00:02:51.904
upon the surface of a guitar
as the music plays

00:02:53.951 --> 00:02:57.561
Now let’s add a video of those
moving hands.

00:03:00.464 --> 00:03:02.644
And let’s add some moving wheat

00:03:02.644 --> 00:03:05.024
with a certain cast of light.

00:03:05.758 --> 00:03:08.768
Let’s gather ourselves.

00:03:09.223 --> 00:03:11.805
Let’s breathe in deeply.

00:03:12.909 --> 00:03:15.909
And breathe out together.

00:03:17.377 --> 00:03:20.517
Let’s see what happens.

00:03:21.315 --> 00:03:24.655
[sound of phone bumping a guitar;
distant sounds of birds]

00:03:32.673 --> 00:03:39.133
[guitar strumming; sounds of birds]

00:03:39.695 --> 00:03:45.389 line:1
♪ I walk in the rain
from time to time.

00:03:47.491 --> 00:03:51.124 line:1
I feel the drops upon my face

00:03:51.124 --> 00:03:56.337 line:1
and see them as they glisten
in the light,

00:03:58.227 --> 00:04:07.099 line:1
so bright, on the wheelbarrow. ♪

00:04:07.812 --> 00:04:11.812 line:1
[Guitar strumming]

00:04:12.879 --> 00:04:17.710
♪ The smell of sweet gardenia in the air.

00:04:20.249 --> 00:04:23.959 line:1
There’s a scratching in the dirt nearby

00:04:23.962 --> 00:04:26.441 line:1
and you wonder why

00:04:27.657 --> 00:04:29.987 line:1
And you turn to hear

00:04:30.914 --> 00:04:33.164 line:1
And your eye is clear

00:04:34.497 --> 00:04:40.720 line:1
As the birds appear. ♪

00:04:41.154 --> 00:04:51.262 line:1
[Guitar strumming]

00:04:52.696 --> 00:04:56.696
♪ I will walk beside you 'til the end.

00:04:59.865 --> 00:05:02.291 line:1
And we will just grow closer

00:05:02.791 --> 00:05:06.211 line:1
with each tender hour we spend,

00:05:06.582 --> 00:05:09.032 line:1
looking out upon the garden

00:05:09.164 --> 00:05:13.164 line:1
as it reaches toward the rain shower, ♪

00:05:13.857 --> 00:05:16.327 line:1
[Guitar strumming]

00:05:16.950 --> 00:05:19.050 line:1
♪ like a friend.

00:05:20.214 --> 00:05:23.168 line:1
'Cause on you and I together

00:05:23.249 --> 00:05:27.249 line:1
and the chickens and the weather,

00:05:29.505 --> 00:05:31.970 line:1
so much depends. ♪

